  "prompt": "What's the best way to calculate percentage off of something?",
  "response": "To calculate the percentage off of something, follow these steps:\n\n1. **Determine the Original Price**: Let's call this \\( P \\).\n\n2. **Identify the Discount Percentage**: Let's call this \\( D \\% \\).\n\n3. **Calculate the Discount Amount**: Multiply the original price by the discount percentage (expressed as a decimal).\n\n   \\[\n   \\text{Discount Amount} = P \\times \\left( \\frac{D}{100} \\right)\n   \\]\n\n4. **Determine the Final Price**: Subtract the discount amount from the original price.\n\n   \\[\n   \\text{Final Price} = P - \\text{Discount Amount}\n   \\]\n\n### Example\n\nSuppose you have an item that costs \\$50 and it's on sale for 20% off.\n\n1. **Original Price (\\( P \\))**: \\$50\n\n2. **Discount Percentage (\\( D \\% \\))**: 20%\n\n3. **Calculate the Discount Amount**:\n\n   \\[\n   \\text{Discount Amount} = 50 \\times \\left( \\frac{20}{100} \\right) = 50 \\times 0.20 = \\$10\n   \\]\n\n4. **Determine the Final Price**:\n\n   \\[\n   \\text{Final Price} = 50 - 10 = \\$40\n   \\]\n\nSo, the final price after a 20% discount is \\$40.\n\n### Shortcut Formula\n\nYou can also calculate the final price directly using this formula:\n\n\\[\n\\text{Final Price} = P \\times \\left( 1 - \\frac{D}{100} \\right)\n\\]\n\nUsing the example above:\n\n\\[\n\\text{Final Price} = 50 \\times (1 - 0.20) = 50 \\times 0.80 = \\$40\n\\]\n\nBoth methods will give you the same result. Choose the one that you find most convenient!",
